\newcommand{\scientific}[1]{\num[round-precision=4,round-mode=figures,scientific-notation=true]{#1}}
The molar mass of glucose is $180.16$g mol$^{-1}$.\\
The number of moles $=$ mass $\div$ molar mass $=\dfrac{5.00}{180.2}=0.0278$ moles.\\
Therefore the number of molecules $=$ moles $\times$ Avogadro's number 
$=0.0278\times(\scientific{6.0220e+23})
=\scientific{1.6713e+22}$ molecules.
\newcommand{\scientific}[1]{\num[round-precision=4,round-mode=figures,scientific-notation=true]{#1}}
\scientific{1.6713e+22}
Calculate the number of molecules in 5.00g of glucose powder $(C_6H_{12}O_6)$.
